<exercise checkit-seed="0007" checkit-slug="L3" checkit-title="Equivalent Statements">
    <statement>
        <p>
        Are the following statements logically equivalent? Use truth tables with the symbols P and Q to determine the answer. Make sure your tables are in the standard order.
            <ol>
                <li>(it is false that I slept poorly last night) implies I exercise regularly</li>
                <li>(I slept poorly last night and I exercise regularly) implies (I slept poorly last night or I exercise regularly)</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
        <p> In symbols, the first statement is <m>( \sim P) \rightarrow Q</m> and the second is <m>(P \wedge Q) \rightarrow (P \vee Q)</m>. The two statements are inequivalent, as you can see by the final column of their truth tables.</p>
        <m>
        \begin{array}{llcc} P &amp; Q &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; ( \sim P) \rightarrow Q \\ \hline \text{True} &amp; \text{True} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \text{True} &amp; \text{False} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \text{False} &amp; \text{True} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \text{False} &amp; \text{False} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{False} \\ \end{array}
        </m>
        <m>
        \begin{array}{llcc} P &amp; Q &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; (P \wedge Q) \rightarrow (P \vee Q) \\ \hline \text{True} &amp; \text{True} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \text{True} &amp; \text{False} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \text{False} &amp; \text{True} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \text{False} &amp; \text{False} &amp;  &amp; \cdots &amp; \text{True} \\ \end{array}
        </m>
    </answer>
</exercise>
